Calls recorded remotely over Inishbofin, an island off the west coast of Co. Galway, Republic of Ireland.  Several Greylags passed overhead in the early morning. It seems that the main calls are from two birds in company (so one might be male, the other female) with a few more distant others calling in the background.  Classic Greylag calls include a triple 'guh, guh, guh' that can be just two notes or up to five in a row. You can hear the 'triple guh' at a few points in the clip: at 0:09 (faint, from a more distant bird), twice in succession just after 0:14, and over the closing seconds from 0:21. Other typical calls are the loud wheezy cough combined with just two 'guh guh' repeats (at 0:01, 0:04 and so on for the next three seconds). Listening to these calls, it appears that one bird is answering the other. Another call is a see-sawing double note from 0:10 for the next four seconds.  The clip evokes a feel for the west of Ireland - a WREN sings from 0:02, SKYLARKS are obvious right from the start and again from 0:20, a CHOUGH calls at 0:06.
